{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641590"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:28:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:28:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17889"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17889"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.21,0.04,0.13,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10603"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78481"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10603"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17889"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63844"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10068"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24715"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78481"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following enzymes is favoured when PFK is inactivated by PKA?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (FBPase1)","Fructose-2,6-bisphosphatase (FBPase2)","Hexokinase","Pyruvate kinase","Glucose-6-phosphatase"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring fasting, the body needs to produce glucose through gluconeogenesis to maintain blood sugar levels. \u003Cstrong\u003EFructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (FBPase1)\u003C/strong\u003E is a key enzyme in gluconeogenesis that converts fructose-1,6-bisphosphate to fructose-6-phosphate, effectively reversing the action of phosphofructokinase (PFK) in glycolysis. When PFK is inactivated by phosphorylation through protein kinase A (PKA), the activity of FBPase1 is favoured, promoting gluconeogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFructose-2,6-bisphosphatase (FBPase2)\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in the regulation of fructose-2,6-bisphosphate levels, which in turn regulates PFK and FBPase1 activity. However, it is not directly favoured by the inactivation of PFK.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHexokinase\u003C/strong\u003E is an enzyme involved in the initial steps of glycolysis, converting glucose to glucose-6-phosphate. It is not directly involved in gluconeogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyruvate kinase\u003C/strong\u003E is another glycolytic enzyme that catalyses the conversion of phosphoenolpyruvate to pyruvate. Its activity is reduced during gluconeogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-6-phosphatase\u003C/strong\u003E is an enzyme involved in the final step of gluconeogenesis, converting glucose-6-phosphate to glucose. While it is important in gluconeogenesis, it is not directly favoured by the inactivation of PFK.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Phosphorylation of phosphofructokinase (PFK) by protein kinase A (PKA) inactivates it, reducing glycolysis.","Fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (FBPase1) is favoured when PFK is inactivated, promoting gluconeogenesis."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Judge A, Dodd MS. Metabolism. Essays Biochem. 2020 Oct 8;64(4):607-647. doi: 10.1042/EBC20190041. PMID: 32830223; PMCID: PMC7545035","Wang Y, Wu R. The Effect of Fasting on Human Metabolism and Psychological Health. Dis Markers. 2022 Jan 5;2022:5653739. doi: 10.1155/2022/5653739. PMID: 35035610; PMCID: PMC8754590","Nakrani MN, Wineland RH, Anjum F. Physiology, Glucose Metabolism. 2023 Jul 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809434","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568. PMID: 33397651; PMCID: PMC7778149"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63844"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17889"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63844"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T21:44:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T00:02:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10603"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78481"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position"